    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Verbascum cylleneum improperly include interacting with medications, which may be due to the plant's bioactive compounds competing with or altering the activity of prescribed drugs. Additionally, Verbascum cylleneum can exacerbate allergies, particularly respiratory allergies, by releasing pollen into the air. Furthermore, some individuals may be at risk of inducing an allergic reaction to the plant, including skin irritation, hives, and anaphylaxis. Improper use of Verbascum cylleneum can also cause dizziness and lightheadedness due to its sedative properties. This is because the plant contains volatile compounds that can affect the central nervous system, leading to adverse effects if used in excess or without proper guidance.",
    "uses": "Verbascum cylleneum, also known as Cretan mullein, has been utilized in traditional medicine for its purported health benefits. The plant's leaves and flowers are said to possess anti-inflammatory properties, which may aid in soothing skin irritations and wounds. In traditional folk medicine, Verbascum cylleneum is used to treat a variety of ailments, including fever, coughs, and respiratory issues. Additionally, the plant is believed to have antimicrobial properties, which may help combat infections. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Verbascum cylleneum for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Verbascum cylleneum is classified in the kingdom Plantae, and within the kingdom it is placed in the phylum Angiospermophyta, class Magnoliopsida, order Lamiales, family Scrophulariaceae. This species is often further grouped into the subfamily Scrophularioideae. It belongs to the genus Verbascum, a group of flowering plants commonly known as mulleins. Verbascum cylleneum is native to specific mountainous regions in Greece. The classification reflects the plant's physical characteristics and evolutionary relationships within the plant kingdom.",
    "benefits": "Verbascum cylleneum, also known as Cretan mullein, has been traditionally used in folk medicine for its potential health benefits. The plant is said to have anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties, which may help soothe skin irritations and wounds. Its leaves and flowers are believed to possess antioxidant properties, which could protect against cell damage and oxidative stress. However, more research is needed to confirm the plant's effectiveness and potential health benefits. In traditional medicine, Verbascum cylleneum is often used to treat various ailments, including fever, cough, and respiratory issues.",
    "parts": "Verbascum cylleneum is known for its medicinal properties, but specific information on its medicinal parts is limited. The plant's uses may include antiviral and antimicrobial properties, although more research is needed to confirm these claims. Traditionally, plants in the Verbascum genus have been used in herbal medicine, suggesting that Verbascum cylleneum may also have medicinal applications. However, without more specific information, it's difficult to determine its exact medicinal parts. Further research is necessary to fully understand the plant's potential medicinal uses.",
    "intro": "Verbascum cylleneum, also known as Cretan Mullein, is a biennial herbaceous plant in the Scrophulariaceae family, characterized by its tall stature and white, yellow, or purple flowers. The plant has been used in traditional medicine for its potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant properties, which may aid in treating respiratory issues, wounds, and skin conditions. The bioactive constituents of Verbascum cylleneum include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which contribute to its medicinal properties. In herbal medicine, Verbascum cylleneum is often prepared as a tincture, infusion, or topical cream, and is used to treat coughs, sore throats, and skin irritations."
